ODE VII

‘Do not weep‚ Asterie, for your absent Gyges. He will come back to you with the spring and bring a wealth of Bithynian merchandise. He will come back: he is only detained by the winter in the harbour to which he was driven on his way home. He lies awake at night thinking of you. It is all in vain that his hostess Chloe tries every art to win him, sends emissaries to tell him of her passion and to prove to him from mythology the folly of constancy; he turns a deas ear to it all. Only mind you do as well. Your neighbour Enipeus is a brave young gallant, but don’t open your window if he comes to serenade you.’
